<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>INTERNATIONAL&#174; VT 365 DIESEL ENGINE - REAR COVER, FLYWHEEL, and POWER STEERING GEAR DRIVE - Rear Main
        Seal and Wear Sleeve
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="5">
        <title>Rear Main Seal and Wear Sleeve</title>
        <figure id="f2651307" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd07/D0720.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Figure 459. Starter holes</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Starter hole</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Rear main seal</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use an awl or 1/8 inch drill bit to make two small starter holes 180&#176; apart into rear
                main seal.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>To prevent personal injury or death, wear safety glasses with side shields to protect eyes.</para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="f2651308" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd07/D0721.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Figure 460. Hammer screw in starter hole</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Thread slide hammer screw into one of the starter holes. To remove seal evenly, slide hammer
                on one side, then alternate to other side.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f2651309" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd07/D0723.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Figure 461. Rear main oil seal removal</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove rear oil seal from rear oil seal carrier. Discard oil seal.</para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>When replacing the rear main seal, note that production engines will not have a wear sleeve. Wear
                    sleeves are only available as a service item included with the replacement rear main oil seal.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="f2651310" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd07/D0734.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Figure 462. Rear Wear Sleeve Removal Tool</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install Rear Wear Sleeve Removal Tool . Make sure remover tool half shells are securely in
                place behind wear sleeve prior to applying any force to threaded shaft.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f2651311" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd07/D0735.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Figure 463. Wear sleeve</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Wear sleeve removal tool</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Wear sleeve</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Turn the threaded shaft clockwise until the wear sleeve is free from the crankshaft
                flange.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
